	<!-- <h2></h2> -->
			<div class="longform special_photo post_img fullwidth">
			<img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/elements-copy-day-four.jpg" alt="" class="entry_post"/>
		</div>
				<h1>The Best Villains in Literature Bracket: The Hateful 8</h1>
	<h2>Round Four</h2>
    <div class="inner">
		<div class="post_header_wrapper">
    				</div>
				<div class="author_info" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
			<div class="author_name">By&nbsp;<a href="https://lithub.com/author/literary-hub/" itemprop="url"><span itemprop="name">Literary&nbsp;Hub</span></a></div>
			<div class="author_hr"><hr/></div>
			<div class="publish_date">March 12, 2025</div>
		</div>
		<div class="social_links">
						<a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=lithub&text=The+Best+Villains+in+Literature+Bracket%3A+The+Hateful+8&url=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Fthe-best-villains-in-literature-bracket-the-hateful-8%2F"><span class="social_twitter"></span></a>
			<a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Fthe-best-villains-in-literature-bracket-the-hateful-8%2F&t=The+Best+Villains+in+Literature+Bracket%3A+The+Hateful+8"><span class="social_facebook"></span></a>
					</div>
    <div class="inner">
    	<!-- Begin main content -->
    	<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
    			
										<!-- Begin each blog post -->
						<div class="post_wrapper" style="padding-top:0;">
							<div class="post_inner_wrapper">
						    	<div class="post_wrapper_inner">
										<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
								        
										<p style="text-align: center;">Welcome to the fourth round of Literary Hub’s inaugural Ides of March Madness bracket:<br />
The Best Villains in Literature.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><script id="9b7a21a47fb44523b011db6d4f4cad23">(new Image()).src = 'https://capi.connatix.com/tr/si?token=546998bb-b9c0-4480-8c91-3e307220efff&cid=86b7c382-5e20-4129-84db-dea768f4d688';  cnx.cmd.push(function() {    cnx({      playerId: "546998bb-b9c0-4480-8c91-3e307220efff"    }).render("9b7a21a47fb44523b011db6d4f4cad23");  });</script></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p>Things are coming down to the wire here for our villains, and eight of the nastiest characters in literature have made it this far to the fourth round, which will decide the winner of each of category.</p>
<p><a href="https://lithub.com/the-best-villains-in-literature-bracket-the-not-so-sweet-16">Some surprising results yesterday</a>: King&#8217;s It is out, and Nurse Ratched was bested by O’Brien, his menacing duplicity beating out her electro-shock dominance. Humbert Humbert lost too—pour one out for the Nabokov fans. Although I have to imagine even in defeat, Humbert and Hannibal Lector are probably still getting along and, as a friend texted me, splitting the most pretentious wine in existence. And Satan beat Javert (ACAB).</p>
<p>The more righteous Anti-Villain won in the Medea vs. Gollum match-up. Being covetous of a powerful ring has nothing on a scorned and wrathful Greek. But Tolkien fans still have Sauron to root for in the Monsters corner. Sauron won handily versus Dracula, who got no extra villainy cred for his real estate speculation—vindication for landlords.</p>
<p>Our in-house speculations for how this was going to go haven’t borne out alas; if you want to see our staff picks, we’ve been <a href="https://lithub.com/tag/villains-bracket/">posting our own brackets alongside our thoughts on our favorite villains.</a> Looking at the current field, one of the four from the Authority Figures or Manipulative Bastards sections seems poised to win it all. The Iago versus Hannibal Lector match-up will be interesting. These are two guys who would text “hey can you call me? nothing big, just want to catch-up!” and then convince you to ruin your life. And Sauron versus Kurtz is a fitting pairing—two fallen lieutenants who’ve set themselves up in fortified nests of depravity. Will the otherworldly beat out the all-too-of-this-world?</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p><strong>Who will make it to the final four tomorrow? Voting is now open!</strong></p>
<p>Check out the updated bracket and start voting below:</p>
<p><a href="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/villainsbracketdayfour-copy.jpg"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="250846" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-villains-in-literature-bracket-the-hateful-8/villainsbracketdayfour-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/villainsbracketdayfour-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="2326,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="villainsbracketdayfour copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/villainsbracketdayfour-copy-273x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/villainsbracketdayfour-copy-930x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-250846" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/villainsbracketdayfour-copy.jpg" alt="" width="2326" height="2560" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/villainsbracketdayfour-copy.jpg 2326w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/villainsbracketdayfour-copy-273x300.jpg 273w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/villainsbracketdayfour-copy-930x1024.jpg 930w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/villainsbracketdayfour-copy-768x845.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/villainsbracketdayfour-copy-55x60.jpg 55w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/villainsbracketdayfour-copy-1396x1536.jpg 1396w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/villainsbracketdayfour-copy-1861x2048.jpg 1861w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/villainsbracketdayfour-copy-45x50.jpg 45w" sizes="(max-width: 2326px) 100vw, 2326px" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>[Click for a zoom-enabled version]</em></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Rules</strong></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p>You may be wondering: <em>What makes a villain “best”?</em> That, friends, is really up to you. You can vote for the most iconic villains, the most memorable villains, or the most villainous villains. You can vote for the villain you enjoyed reading about the most, or the one that kept you up at night. You can vote for the cutest villain, if that’s your thing. The point is, there are no rules. Villains are rule-breakers, and so are we.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Voting Schedule</strong></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;"><del><strong>Ignoble Round of 64:</strong> Voting open now until <strong>Sunday, March 9th</strong> at 7:00 PM EST</del></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;"><del><strong>Round of 32 Assholes:</strong> Voting open now, from 10:00 AM – 7:00 PM EST on <strong>Monday, March 10th</strong></del></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;"><del><strong>Not-So-Sweet 16:</strong> Voting open from 10:00 AM – 7:00 PM EST on <strong>Tuesday, March 11th</strong></del></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;"><strong>The Hateful 8:</strong> Voting open from 10:00 AM – 7:00 PM EST on <strong>Wednesday, March 12th</strong></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;"><strong>The Drawn and Quarter Finals:</strong> Voting open from 10:00 AM – 7:00 PM EST on <strong>Thursday, March 13th</strong></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;"><strong>The Final Showdown:</strong> Voting open until Sunday, March 16th at 7:00 PM EST on <strong>Friday, March 14th</strong></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;"><strong>And the Best Villain In Literature will be announced on Monday, March 17th!</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>How To Vote</strong></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p>Same as before: simply select the villain you think should advance, and we’ll tabulate the votes tonight.</p>
<p><a href="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/finger.jpg" class="external" target="_blank"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="244891" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-villains-in-literature-bracket/finger/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/finger.jpg" data-orig-size="301,116" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="finger" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/finger.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/finger.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-244891" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/finger.jpg" alt="" width="301" height="116" data-attachment-id="244891" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-villains-in-literature-bracket/finger/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/finger.jpg" data-orig-size="301,116" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="finger" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/finger.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/finger.jpg" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/finger.jpg 301w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/finger-60x23.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/finger-50x19.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 301px) 100vw, 301px" /></a></p>
<h1 style="text-align: center;">Authority Figures</h1>
<h2 style="text-align: center;">(In charge and insane.)</h2>
<p><a href="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/obriencommander.jpg"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="250844" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-villains-in-literature-bracket-the-hateful-8/obriencommander/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/obriencommander.jpg" data-orig-size="900,300" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="obriencommander" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/obriencommander-300x100.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/obriencommander.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-250844 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/obriencommander.jpg" alt="" width="900" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/obriencommander.jpg 900w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/obriencommander-300x100.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/obriencommander-768x256.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/obriencommander-60x20.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/obriencommander-50x17.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px" /></a></p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><b>O’BRIEN (1) vs. </b><b>THE COMMANDER (14)</b></h2>
<p><strong>(1) O’Brien (George Orwell, <em><a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780451524935" target="_blank" rel="noopener">1984</a>)</em></strong></p>
<p>Our top seed for authoritarians is this extremely memorable villain from one of the most widely read books about villainy. Orwell’s O’Brien combines all the worst villains from the real world into one of the nastiest guys in literature: he’s a fascist, a boss, and a snitch all rolled into one, a sort-of fascist Megazord, if you will.</p>
<p><b>Weapon of Choice:</b> Lying, Rodents, Party-Members-Only Wine<br />
<b>Grim Prediction:</b> “If you want a picture of the future, imagine a boot stamping on a human face—forever.”<br />
<b>2+2:</b> 5</p>
<p><strong>Read:</strong> <a href="https://lithub.com/75-years-of-1984-why-george-orwells-classic-remains-more-relevant-than-ever/">75 Years of <em>1984</em>: Why George Orwell’s Classic Remains More Relevant Than Ever</a> and <a href="https://lithub.com/george-orwells-1984-is-always-just-around-the-corner/">George Orwell’s <em>1984</em> is Always Just Around the Corner</a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>vs.</strong></p>
<p><strong>(14) The Commander (Margaret Atwood, <em><a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780385490818" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Handmaid’s Tale</a>)</em></strong></p>
<p>There are some novels that you wish the world could emulate more — <em>The Handmaid’s Tale</em> is one I wish would <em>stop</em> being so relevant. The Commander is a true and complete bastard, who is addicted to his patriarchal power — he isn’t content with his authority as the unquestioned head of household, he also bends Gilead’s rules to create more ways to control and abuse the women in his life.</p>
<p><b>Patriarchy’s Tools:</b> Scrabble Boards, Privilege<br />
<b>Bad Justification:</b> “You can’t make an omelette without breaking eggs, is what he says.”<br />
<b>Number of Real-Life Villains He’s Similar To:</b> Far Too Many</p>
<p><strong>Read: </strong><a href="https://lithub.com/the-handmaids-tale-adapts-more-than-the-novel-here-is-america/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Handmaid’s Tale </em>Adapts More Than the Novel: Here is America</a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfUwGMOTNm_seDZCD_EBKnnP1xuxf3DwVzwQXcw26zrfZN4DQ/viewform?embedded=true" frameborder="0" width="640" height="463" marginheight="0" marginwidth="0" allowfullscreen="true" mozallowfullscreen="true" webkitallowfullscreen="true"></iframe></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h1><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="245300" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-villains-in-literature-bracket/snake2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/snake2.jpg" data-orig-size="900,116" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="snake2" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/snake2-300x39.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/snake2.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-245300 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/snake2.jpg" alt="" width="900" height="116" data-attachment-id="245300" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-villains-in-literature-bracket/snake2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/snake2.jpg" data-orig-size="900,116" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="snake2" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/snake2-300x39.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/snake2.jpg" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/snake2.jpg 900w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/snake2-300x39.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/snake2-768x99.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/snake2-60x8.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/snake2-50x6.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px" /></h1>
<h1 style="text-align: center;">Manipulative Bastards</h1>
<h2 style="text-align: center;">(Scheme &#8217;til you scream.)</h2>
<p><a href="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/iagolecter.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="250842" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-villains-in-literature-bracket-the-hateful-8/iagolecter/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/iagolecter.jpg" data-orig-size="900,300" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="iagolecter" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/iagolecter-300x100.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/iagolecter.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-250842 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/iagolecter.jpg" alt="" width="900" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/iagolecter.jpg 900w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/iagolecter-300x100.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/iagolecter-768x256.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/iagolecter-60x20.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/iagolecter-50x17.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px" /></a></p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><strong>IAGO (1) vs. </strong><b>HANNIBAL LECTER (3) </b><strong> </strong></h2>
<p><strong>(1) Iago (William Shakespeare, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780743477550" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Othello</em></a>)</strong></p>
<p>Iago is high up on our list, and an all time manipulative bastard. The first guy to claim that he wore his heart on his sleeve was actually scheming up a storm for no discernible reason—a truly two-faced man. If you ever cringe thinking about the relationship drama you got into in your twenties, rest easy there wasn’t an Iago in your friend group.</p>
<p><strong>Manipulates With:</strong> Fatal Workplace Gossip, Handkerchiefs<br />
<strong>Wicked Aside:</strong> “That thinks men honest that but seem to be so,/And will as tenderly be led by the nose/As asses are.”<br />
<strong>Manipulation Count:</strong> Contrives at least 3 fights and 1 demotion</p>
<p><strong>Read:</strong> <a href="https://crimereads.com/poison-in-the-ear-why-iago-is-the-ultimate-thriller-character/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Poison in the Ear: Why Iago is the Ultimate Thriller Character</a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>vs.</strong></p>
<p><strong>(3) Hannibal Lecter (Thomas Harris, <em><a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780425228227" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Red Dragon</a>, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780312924584" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Silence of the Lambs</a></em>, etc.)</strong></p>
<p>When we were putting this list together, we knew immediately that Dr. Lecter would be a top seed. What other villain could turn Fava beans into a scary line? Though real Harris-heads know the famous meal in the <em>book</em> is served with Fava beans and Amarone—not Chianti.</p>
<p><b>Fillets With:</b> His Memory Palace, Big Culinary Choices<br />
<b>Boiling Him Down:</b> “He’s a monster. I think of him as one of those pitiful things that are born in hospitals from time to time. They feed it, and keep it warm, but they don’t put it on the machines and it dies. Lecter is the same way in his head, but he looks normal and nobody could tell.”<br />
<b>Menu of Victims:</b> 28 killed, 7 eaten</p>
<p><strong>Read:</strong> <a href="https://crimereads.com/hannibal-lecter-20-years-later/">Hannibal Lecter: 20 Years Later</a>; <a href="https://crimereads.com/the-silence-of-the-lambs-the-seminal-serial-killer-novel-and-still-the-best/"><em>The Silence of the Lambs</em>: The Seminal Serial Killer Novel, and Still the Best</a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSd7931IodgGbLDs85lvhi3R8FkKnZwNph6Wlk_HHFJyTt3VkA/viewform?embedded=true" frameborder="0" width="640" height="463" marginheight="0" marginwidth="0" allowfullscreen="true" mozallowfullscreen="true" webkitallowfullscreen="true"></iframe></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="245301" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-villains-in-literature-bracket/octo/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/octo.jpg" data-orig-size="900,116" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="octo" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/octo-300x39.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/octo.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-245301 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/octo.jpg" alt="" width="900" height="116" data-attachment-id="245301" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-villains-in-literature-bracket/octo/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/octo.jpg" data-orig-size="900,116" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="octo" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/octo-300x39.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/octo.jpg" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/octo.jpg 900w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/octo-300x39.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/octo-768x99.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/octo-60x8.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/octo-50x6.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px" /></p>
<h1 style="text-align: center;">Monsters &amp; Boogeymen</h1>
<h2 style="text-align: center;">(With fiends like these&#8230;)</h2>
<p><a href="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/kurtzsauron.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="250843" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-villains-in-literature-bracket-the-hateful-8/kurtzsauron/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/kurtzsauron.jpg" data-orig-size="900,300" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="kurtzsauron" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/kurtzsauron-300x100.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/kurtzsauron.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-250843 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/kurtzsauron.jpg" alt="" width="900" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/kurtzsauron.jpg 900w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/kurtzsauron-300x100.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/kurtzsauron-768x256.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/kurtzsauron-60x20.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/kurtzsauron-50x17.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px" /></a></p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><strong>KURTZ (5) vs. </strong><b>SAURON (3)</b></h2>
<p><strong>(5) Kurtz (Joseph Conrad, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780143106586" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Heart of Darkness</em></a>)</strong></p>
<p>A thoroughly evil man, Kurtz uses a mandate from a colonizing corporation to fashion himself as a mad demigod who rules over a cruel African outpost. Conrad’s novella was based on his own experiences on a Belgian steamer, and Kurtz is likely an amalgam of various violent Europeans who terrorized Africa—he’s one of literature’s most indelible sociopaths.</p>
<p><b>Weapon of Choice:</b> Exploitative Colonial Capitalism, Monologues<br />
<b>Famous Last Words:</b> “The horror! The horror!”<br />
<b>Kilometers He’s Hidden Himself Up River:</b> &gt;65</p>
<p><strong>Read:</strong> <a href="https://lithub.com/invasion-is-a-structure-not-an-event-on-settler-colonialism-and-joseph-conrads-heart-of-darkness/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">“Invasion is a Structure Not an Event.” On Settler Colonialism and Joseph Conrad’s <em>Heart of Darkness</em></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>vs.</strong></p>
<p><strong>(3) Sauron (J.R.R. Tolkien, <em><a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780345538376" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Lord of the Rings</a></em>)</strong></p>
<p>The Lidless Eye, The Monster from Mordor, The Rascal with the Rings—Sauron’s the all-seeing Orcs’ mate you love to hate. As readers, we’re told very little about Sauron’s appearance and we never meet him, but we see his presence everywhere. He’s a pervasive evil influence corrupting Middle Earth, a hazy darkness with vast influence. The one thing he seems incapable of doing, though, is holding onto jewelry—take off your all-powerful rings before a swordfight, dude! It’s like swimming with your wedding ring on: don’t do it!</p>
<p><b>His Horde Includes:</b> Nazgûl, Uruks, Easterlings, Haradrim, Trolls, Tolkein Nerds Correcting Factual Inaccuracies in Articles Like This One<br />
<b>The Eye Gazes on Thee:</b> “Its wrath blazed like a sudden flame and its fear was like a great black smoke, for it knew its deadly peril, the thread upon which hung its doom.”<br />
<b>Rings To Rule Them All:</b> 1</p>
<p><strong>Read:</strong> <a href="https://lithub.com/theres-no-invention-in-the-void-read-a-handwritten-letter-from-j-r-r-tolkien-on-the-origins-of-middle-earth/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">“There’s no invention in the void.” Read a letter from J.R.R. Tolkien on the origins of Middle-earth.</a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfqKoiIDKcBbmDSSaMqlhxW_6SFdP-tRhVSRsCuGjmrF11sSA/viewform?embedded=true" frameborder="0" width="640" height="463" marginheight="0" marginwidth="0" allowfullscreen="true" mozallowfullscreen="true" webkitallowfullscreen="true"></iframe></p>
<h1><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="245302" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-villains-in-literature-bracket/ice-4/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/ice.jpg" data-orig-size="900,116" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="ice" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/ice-300x39.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/ice.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-245302 size-full" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/ice.jpg" alt="" width="900" height="116" data-attachment-id="245302" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-best-villains-in-literature-bracket/ice-4/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/ice.jpg" data-orig-size="900,116" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="ice" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/ice-300x39.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/ice.jpg" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/ice.jpg